sfer hose failure due to a sudden hose uncoupling while pumping from the storage tank to the tanker truck.  LNG is released at a rate of 175 gallons per minute, which is the transfer pump rate.  A release duration of 1 minute has been assumed for the ACS.  This is a conservative assumption based on operator experience.  It encompasses time for the operator to realize what is occurring, travel to the pump control panel, and push the off-button.  No passive or active mitigation measures present at the facility have been considered in the evaluation of the ACS.  This release scenario has been modeled as both as a vapor cloud fire and a pool fire to determine which type of scenario produces the most conservative results.  

The amount of methane released under each type of scenario is 618 pounds.  The pool fire scenario results in an endpoint distance of 0.03 miles; the endpoint for this scenario is a thermal flux of 5 kw/m2.  The vapor cloud fire scenario results in an endpoint distance of 0.01 miles; the endpoint for this scenario is a concentration less than the lower flammability limit for methane (5 percent).

Of the two types of scenarios, the pool fire scenario provides the most conservative results for the ACS radius of influence.  Therefore, the radius of influence for this scenario has been used in determining the exposed population and public and environmental receptors for the ACS.  The residential population affected under the ACS is 0 people. 

Prevention Program

The LNG covered process is subject to Program 3 prevention program requirements because it is subject to OSHA?s PSM standards and is not eligible for Program 1.  The PG&E Program 3 prevention program includes the following:
?Process Safety Information;
?Process Hazard Review;
?Operating Procedures;
?Training;
?Mechanical Integrity;
?Management of Change;
?Pre-Startup Safety Review;
?Compliance Audits;
?Incident Investigations;
?Employee Participation;
?Hot Work Permit; and
?Contractors.

